# Confidential Voting Contract — Full Implementation

## Design

In a standard on-chain vote, every vote is public. With fhEVM, each voter submits an encrypted vote (0 = No, 1 = Yes). The contract accumulates votes by adding ciphertexts. The tally is only revealed after the owner ends the voting period and the Gateway decrypts the final result.

Properties:
- Individual votes are permanently private (no reveal, even after voting ends)
- Tally is computed entirely in ciphertext during the voting period
- Result is revealed atomically when `endVoting()` is called
- Each address may vote exactly once

## Full Solidity Contract

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.24;

import "fhevm/lib/TFHE.sol";
import "fhevm/config/ZamaFHEVMConfig.sol";
import "fhevm/gateway/GatewayCaller.sol";

contract EncryptedVoting is SepoliaZamaFHEVMConfig, SepoliaZamaGatewayConfig, GatewayCaller {
    address public owner;
    bool public votingOpen;
    uint256 public plaintextTally;  // set after decryption
    bool public resultRevealed;

    euint64 private encryptedTally;
    mapping(address => bool) public hasVoted;
    uint256 public voterCount;

    event VoteCast(address indexed voter);
    event VotingEnded(uint256 requestId);
    event ResultRevealed(uint256 tally);

    modifier onlyOwner() {
        require(msg.sender == owner, "Not owner");
        _;
    }

    constructor() {
        owner = msg.sender;
        votingOpen = true;
        // Initialize tally to encrypted 0
        encryptedTally = TFHE.asEuint64(0);
        TFHE.allow(encryptedTally, address(this));
    }

    function vote(einput encryptedVote, bytes calldata inputProof) external {
        require(votingOpen, "Voting closed");
        require(!hasVoted[msg.sender], "Already voted");

        // Decode and validate: value must be 0 or 1
        euint64 vote_ = TFHE.asEuint64(encryptedVote, inputProof);

        // Add encrypted vote to tally
        encryptedTally = TFHE.add(encryptedTally, vote_);
        TFHE.allow(encryptedTally, address(this));

        hasVoted[msg.sender] = true;
        voterCount++;
        emit VoteCast(msg.sender);
    }

    function endVoting() external onlyOwner {
        require(votingOpen, "Already ended");
        votingOpen = false;

        // Request Gateway to decrypt the final tally
        uint256[] memory cts = new uint256[](1);
        cts[0] = Gateway.toUint256(encryptedTally);
        uint256 requestId = Gateway.requestDecryption(
            cts,
            this.decryptionCallback.selector,
            0,
            block.timestamp + 100,
            false
        );
        emit VotingEnded(requestId);
    }

    function decryptionCallback(
        uint256 /*requestId*/,
        uint64 result
    ) external onlyGateway {
        plaintextTally = result;
        resultRevealed = true;
        emit ResultRevealed(result);
    }
}
```

## Frontend Flow

```typescript
// 1. Encrypt the vote (1 = Yes, 0 = No)
const instance = await createInstance({ network, gatewayUrl })
const encrypted = instance.encrypt64(1n)  // voting Yes

// 2. Submit vote
await voting.vote(encrypted.handles[0], encrypted.inputProof)

// 3. Wait for result after owner calls endVoting()
// Poll or listen for ResultRevealed event
voting.on('ResultRevealed', (tally) => {
  console.log(`Final Yes votes: ${tally} / ${await voting.voterCount()}`)
})
```

## Security Notes

- Individual votes are never revealed — not even to the contract owner
- The tally is a single encrypted integer; no partial results leak during voting
- The owner can end voting at any time, but cannot manipulate individual votes
- For production: add minimum voting period, quorum requirements, and multi-sig on `endVoting`

## vs. Public On-chain Voting

| Property | Public Voting | Encrypted Voting |
|----------|--------------|------------------|
| Vote privacy | None | Full |
| Tally during vote | Visible | Hidden |
| Gas cost | Low | Higher (~3x) |
| Coercion resistance | Low | High |
| Auditability | Full | Tally only |
